{
  "explanation": "The defendant has been convicted of embezzling $25,000 from their employer, a serious offense that involves a profound breach of fiduciary trust. In determining the appropriate sentence, I must weigh both aggravating and mitigating factors. The mitigating factors here are substantial: the defendant has no prior criminal record, and they have already made efforts to partially repay the stolen funds, indicating remorse and a willingness to make the victim whole. The courtroom outburst suggesting a 10-year sentence is entirely disregarded, as it is both procedurally irrelevant and wildly disproportionate for a first-time, non-violent white-collar offense of this financial magnitude. The justice system aims to balance punishment, deterrence, and rehabilitation. While the breach of trust warrants a period of confinement, a prolonged sentence would hinder the defendant's ability to re-enter the workforce and pay the remaining restitution. Therefore, a modest period of incarceration is appropriate to reflect the seriousness of the crime, to be followed by probation and a mandate to complete full restitution.",
  "verdict": 6
}
